                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p33776f9n/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>feeling against <persName>Mr. DeSola</persName>, or <persName>Dr. Raphall</persName>.\n                It was no<lb/> breach of friendship in the former becoming a<lb/> candidate, when\n                applications were invited by pub=<lb/>=lic advertisement; and you must admit that\n                his<lb/> offering neither injured, nor <sic>benefitted</sic> you. Your<lb/> enemies\n                were determined to put you down the<lb/> same crew had been striving for that object\n                for<lb/> twenty five years, and the wonder is that you<lb/> held your ground so\n                long. Now as to <persName>Dr. Rs.</persName> Giving<lb/> a <hi rend=\"underline\"\n                    >certificate</hi> of <hi rend=\"underline\">qualification</hi>, I have no\n                hesi=<lb/>=tancy in saying that <hi rend=\"underline\">he</hi>, and <hi\n                    rend=\"underline\">every other man</hi><lb/>\n                <hi rend=\"underline\">is bound</hi> by every principle of honor, and duty<lb/> to\n                give such a certificate whenever called on to<lb/> do so, if the party is capable. I\n                have given cer=<lb/>=tificates of qualification, when at the same<lb/> time I\n                desired an other equally capable to<lb/> receive the appointment. Try, my friend,\n                to<lb/> think differently of mankind—do not, I pray you,<lb/> suppose that every\n                body is against you. There<lb/> is good and evil in this world—and all of us\n                have<lb/> our respective shares. You may remember<lb/> an anecdote of <persName>Dr.\n                    Franklin</persName>. When about leaving<lb/>\n                <placeName>Boston</placeName> for his voyage of life, he went to see an old<lb/>\n                friend, who at his departure took him through<lb/> a dark passage by which he struck\n                his head against<lb/> a beam. The old man said, let this teach you<lb/> that you\n                must often stoop if you want to<lb/> pass through life without difficulty.\n                    <persName>Franklin</persName><lb/> took the hint, &amp; you know his\n                history.</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p33776f9n/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
            }
